collection: The Siege and Commune of Paris, 1870-1871
description: Illustrated with thirty-four albumen prints depicting buildings and monuments burned during the Commune uprising.  Images include the Hôtel de Ville and the Tuileries Palace before the destruction of the Commune, as well as interior and exterior views of these buildings after they had been torched. Other monuments include the gutted Préfecture de police, the Ministère des finances, the interior of the Palais de justice, and the toppled Colonne Vendôme. One startling image shows melted oil drums in a grenier d'abondance. Views of the destruction on the streets of Paris include views down the rue de Rivoli, the rue Royale, the rue de Bac, and the barely recognizable carrefour de la Croix-Rouge. Other residential areas of Paris affected by the Commune include Neuilly, Auteuil and St. Cloud. One street scene in Auteuil shows that reconstruction had already begun.|Mounted photographs
